<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 93 / UK Company News: L&amp;G reports increased life and pension
business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEGAL &amp; General, the life and general insurer, reported a strong increase in
new pension and life business in the first half of 1993, indicating recovery
after a sharp decline in new business at the same stage of last year.
Mr David Prosser, chief executive, said the figures reflected 'the gradual
emergence of the economy from recession and a more focused approach to the
management of our distribution channels.'
L&amp;G's distribution network of direct sales and tied agency sales forces has
contracted sharply since 1989 and has only just begun to stabilise.
The company was boosted by strong growth of income from single premiums in
the UK. Life business single premiums were sharply ahead at Pounds 150.3m,
of which Pounds 140.4m came from unitised with-profit bonds.
Single premium income from pensions rose 66 per cent to Pounds 335.8m.
Overseas single premiums rose by 50 per cent to Pounds 79.2m. Overall single
premium business increased 96 per cent to Pounds 99.6m.
With consumers still lacking confidence to make long-term financial
commitments, the growth of new annual business premium income was slower.
Premiums from UK life business rose 3 per cent to Pounds 38.1m in the first
six months of 1993, while income from UK pensions business remained level at
Pounds 34.7m.
Overseas annual business premium income amounted to Pounds 25.5m (Pounds
21m).
</TEXT>
