<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 93 / Chase Manhattan accelerates improvement in credit quality
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CHASE Manhattan's emergence from the credit problems that have bedevilled it
since the late 1980s was confirmed yesterday as it revealed a marked
improvement in credit quality during the second quarter.
A falling charge for possible credit losses, plus strong foreign exchange
and other trading income pushed net income for the period ahead to Dollars
233m, up from Dollars 152m in the same period a year earlier. Earnings per
share rose to Dollars 1.20, from Dollars 0.83.
Chase, battered by problems on US commercial property lending at the turn of
the decade, had moved earlier this year to isolate Dollars 2bn of troubled
property loans and to bolster its balance sheet with the sale of Dollars
750m of new equity.
Yesterday, the US's sixth biggest bank reported a provision of Dollars 225m
against possible credit losses in the second quarter, Dollars 70m lower than
a year earlier and down from Dollars 360m in the first quarter. Analysts saw
this as a sign of faster-than-expected improvement in credit quality.
Credit quality was also reflected in the increase in the proportion of
troubled loans covered by loan-loss reserves, to 82 per cent from 67 per
cent.
Net interest income advanced to Dollars 894m from Dollars 869m in the same
period in 1992, and the bank's net interest margin rose from 4.03 per cent
to 4.1 per cent. The bank's cost/income ratio, a key measure of efficiency,
fell to 62 per cent, down marginally from the first quarter. 'The aggressive
action programme we implemented in the second quarter is already beginning
to bolster our earnings momentum,' said Mr Tom Labrecque, chairman.
Trading in foreign exchange and derivatives, and in lesser-developed country
(ldc) markets, pushed non-interest revenues up by Dollars 100m to Dollars
693m year-on-year. Foreign exchange trading made Dollars 85m (up from
Dollars 61m), while derivatives trading brought in Dollars 54m and the ldc
markets Dollars 35m. Non-interest income was held back, though, by a Dollars
27m fall in consumer banking fees as borrowers moved to refinance mortgage
loans.
Tier one capital ratio climbed to 7.74 per cent, from 6.1 per cent.
</TEXT>
