<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 93 / Carsberg threatens Abta with legal action over rule
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR BRYAN Carsberg, director-general of fair trading, has threatened to take
legal action against the Association of British Travel Agents unless it
allows tour operators which are not members of the association to sell their
holidays through Abta agents.
Sir Bryan's threat came in a letter to the Association of Independent Tour
Operators (Aito) which wrote to him complaining that some of its members had
had difficulty joining Abta.
As a result, they had been unable to sell their holidays through
Abta-affiliated outlets because an Abta rule stipulates its agents should
sell only foreign holidays provided by association members.
The rule, known as Stabiliser, was introduced in 1965. In 1982, the
Restrictive Practices Court ruled it was in the public interest and could be
legally enforced as it ensured customers were protected provided they bought
holidays from Abta members.
The legality of the Abta rule was thrown into doubt, however, by the
introduction at the beginning of this year of new EC rules on package
holidays. These require all providers of package holidays, whether Abta
members or not, to ensure customers' money is adequately protected.
Sir Bryan made it clear in his letter to Aito that he believed Abta's
Stabiliser should be abolished now that the new rules had come into force.
He said: 'Abta are aware that I am concerned about the continuation of
Stabiliser, which is effectively tying your members who wish to sell
overseas package holidays through Abta agents to (the association). If Abta
do not end it, I may apply to the court for leave to have the court's
earlier decision which upheld Stabiliser reviewed.'
Aito says its members have been told they can only join Abta if they arrange
Abta bonds for their road and ferry holidays. Air holidays are bonded by the
Civil Aviation Authority. Aito says it has its own bonding arrangements
which cover members' surface travel holidays and these should be sufficient.
In his letter, Sir Bryan agreed, saying he thought Abta should be prepared
to accept the financial protection of any company which complied with the
new regulations.
Abta said yesterday it was not prepared to accept Aito's financial
guarantees because it was concerned about the adequacy of back-up
arrangements if the bonds proved insufficient.
Abta's national council agreed last month that Stabiliser would have to end.
As this would require an extraordinary general meeting, it did not believe
it could happen before September.
</TEXT>
