<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 93 / Pru chief urges talks on fees disclosure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Mick Newmarch, chief executive of Prudential Corporation, the UK's
largest life insurance company, has called on the Office of Fair Trading to
have direct discussions with the life insurance industry on disclosure.
In March the OFT attacked a proposal from the Securities and Investments
Board and other City self-regulatory organisations for the life insurance
industry, saying it contained seriously anti-competitive elements.
The OFT urged that independent financial advisers be required to disclose
the amount of commission they will earn from prospective customers, that
life insurers should spell out the surrender value in each year of a
policy's life until maturity, that the effect of costs in investment returns
be demonstrated by using each company's own charges, and that low-cost sales
outlets be allowed to charge less for the same product than high-cost
outlets.
In a seven-page letter to the OFT last week Mr Newmarch took issue with its
proposals and said the self-regulating organisations should have no role in
deciding on disclosure rules.
'The primary relationship needs to be with the industry - represented by
leading practitioners and its trade associations - not with the regulatory
bodies,' he wrote.
He said the price comparison data which the OFT sought would probably be of
little use.
'The provision of comparative performance data is less important to saver
protection than transparency on the terms which will govern the build-up of
value in the product, and the policyholder's access to the funds built up,'
he said.
Mr Newmarch proposes that sales agents be required to disclose the
customer's contractual obligation to pay premiums, the terms governing the
build-up of policy proceeds and customer access to them, the charges which
apply to the separate elements of the contract such as investment management
or life insurance premiums, and the basis for determining charges.
People, Page 10
</TEXT>
