<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Smith wins vote backing at NEC
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR'S ruling national executive committee last night endorsed
controversial proposals by party leader Mr John Smith for
one-member-one-vote in the selection of parliamentary candidates.
The NEC voted by 20 votes to seven in favour of the 'consensus' Mr Smith
said was achieved at a meeting between Labour MPs and union representatives
last week.
But the decision makes it more likely the leadership will face a battle at
the party's annual conference in September, since some of Britain's largest
unions including the GMB and the TGWU have made clear they are still opposed
to parts of the plan.
The trade union reform group's report would form the basis of rule changes
to be put to the conference. Mr Smith said at the end of the meeting: 'I
recommend (the proposals) to the party and believe (they) will greatly
strengthen both Labour party democracy and the links between the Labour
party and the trade unions and their members.'
But NEC member Mr Dan Duffy, chairman of the TGWU general union, said: 'As
far as we're concerned the present proposals will reduce the links and will
emasculate the trade union movement.'
He added: 'If the proposals are still the same as they are at present, we
will be arguing against them.'
