<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Major tested by establishment thorn
in his side - Gillian Tett says simple questions lie at the heart of Lord
Rees-Mogg's move for judicial review of the Maastricht treaty
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EVEN IF short-term politics was the motive for Lord Rees-Mogg's application
for judicial review of the Maastricht ratification, his decision to take the
political battle to the courts has revived a legal debate which has dogged
the constitution for centuries.
The questions at the heart of his application are relatively simple. How far
can the government operate independently from parliament? And in the absence
of a written constitution, who decides whether government or parliament is
more powerful?
Professor Michael Zander, a constitutional expert at the London School of
Economics, said: 'It's a major constitutional issue that has been raised. If
Lord Rees-Mogg succeeds it would put the government in very serious
difficulties.'
Lord Rees-Mogg's case is based on the argument that the bill before
parliament does not exactly match the Maastricht treaty signed by Mr John
Major last year. Lord Rees-Mogg argues that the government does not have the
right to endorse a treaty when only part of it has been approved by
parliament.
He cites two potential examples of the mismatch. The first is that the
treaty signed in Maastricht did not envisage that Britain would participate
in the social chapter. So if the Commons endorses the social chapter on
Thursday, it would endorse something Mr Major did not sign.
The second, more significant, issue is that the treaty contains protocols
relating to defence and foreign policy, which do not all appear in the bill.
The government claims the royal prerogative - the tradition which gives the
executive the right to take decisions - allows it to ratify treaties without
parliamentary approval.
Mr Leolin Price QC, Lord Rees-Mogg's barrister, who argues that this is
'perhaps the most important constitutional issue to be faced by the courts
for 300 years', says the government cannot use the royal prerogative to hand
to Europe its powers on decisions such as monetary union or foreign policy.
Legal experts were yesterday sceptical about Lord Rees-Mogg's chances of
success in the courts - even though the trend in recent constitutional
battles has been for parliament to gain powers at the expense of the
executive.
Mr Paul Craig, constitutional expert at Oxford University, said the issue of
'mismatch' between the treaty and bill was by no means clear cut -
parliament does have to approve treaties when they affect domestic British
law, but has usually approved an abridged version of such treaties.
'It's quite common for the bills to be shorter,' says Mr Craig, who cites
the original EC treaty as a crucial example of this - the full treaty had
more than 230 articles, while the 1972 bill passed by parliament was 'tiny,
only a few pages'.
Professor Trevor Hartley, an expert on EC law, says the tradition of royal
prerogative is on the government's side: 'Any British government in theory
can more or less act as it wants in foreign affairs. So it could go ahead
and ratify it without parliament - although of course that would be
politically difficult.' He adds that the problem would only arise with
'internal laws', which could, in theory, be referred to the British courts.
The government has said the opt-out on the social chapter means that British
law is not affected by the treaty. Lord Rees-Mogg argues that Britain could
still be bound by the rulings of the European courts on this matter.
For critics of the government this debate illustrates the need for a written
constitution to clarify the balance between parliament and government - or
even, some argue, to give parliament clear supremacy over the government.
Mr Craig predicts that given the constitutional significance of the case it
will go all the way to the House of Lords.
</TEXT>
<XX>
