<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Profile of Lord Rees-Mogg
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD Rees-Mogg, Baron of Hinton Blewitt and former editor of The Times, has
always liked novelty and mischief and has argued eccentric views with
lucidity and passion, Raymond Snoddy writes.
At the same time he has been developing a deeply gloomy view of Britain
which he recently dubbed the Scarborough Syndrome after a hotel perched on a
clifftop which started to sink into the sea.
'We lose to America in football, to Brussels in European policy, to Japan in
industry, to secularism in the Church and our economic policy has been a
disaster,' Lord Rees-Mogg wrote recently in The Times.
His legal challenge to the Maastricht bill, financed at least in part by Sir
James Goldsmith, the financier, brings together all Lord Rees-Mogg's taste
for novelty and mischief, passion and gloom in a single theatrical
performance in the High Court.
He once predicted the coming of an new ice age, before global warming
diverted people's attention. He supported former US president Richard Nixon
in preference to the Washington Post over Watergate, and more recently
co-authored a book forecasting doom and disaster and the end of
civilisation.
Lord Rees-Mogg is one of the sharpest thorns in the side of Mr John Major,
who he described as a 'B-category' PM to be compared with such Tory premiers
as Chamberlain and Eden who were so weakened by crisis that they were
finally ousted.
Lord Rees-Mogg also likes heroes, however grotesque. He finds the pop singer
Madonna a more exciting role model than German chancellor Helmut Kohl. But
he admires former prime minister Margaret Thatcher much more than Madonna.
'The outstanding example of greatness in modern Britain has been Margaret
Thatcher. Her whole image is one of energy, of which as prime minister she
seemed to have almost inexhaustible reserves,' he said.
Lord Rees-Mogg's profile has been revived as a patrician columnist and
controversialist of extreme opinions.
Asked recently whether there was any area in which he felt unqualified to
make a judgment, he replied: 'Clearly there are lots of subjects on which I
am unqualified to talk about. I wouldn't write an article about
mountain-climbing.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
