<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 93 / Watchdog to quiz banks on records
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMAS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BANKS are to be asked what information they keep on customers, the office of
the data protection registrar said yesterday, Steve Thomas writes.
The move followed Labour criticism of National Westminster Bank's policy of
holding files on the political affiliations and religious opinions of
customers.
Mr Francis Aldhouse, the deputy data protection registrar, said: 'We will be
taking this issue up with all leading banks because we are not quite sure
what the situation is.' He said the holding of information about political
affiliations was 'potentially sensitive' and suggested customers were
entitled to an explanation.
The bank said it did not solicit political and religious information but
recorded data it judged helpful in building a profile of customers.
It had permission from the data protection registrar, Mr Eric Howe, to hold
such information.
</TEXT>
