FT  20 JUL 93 / Monks leads TUC drive to preserve check-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   A DRIVE to co-ordinate union campaigns to preserve check-off schemes
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
under which employers debit union subscriptions from salaries - was launched
yesterday by Mr John Monks, who will be the new general secretary of the
Trades Union Congress.
The appointment of Mr Monks, now deputy general secretary of the TUC, was
confirmed yesterday. As sole candidate he was nominated by 31 unions
representing 87 per cent of total TUC membership.
Mr Monks will take over from Mr Norman Willis, who retires on September 10
at the end of this year's annual congress.
Mr Monks said one of his main concerns was to raise the morale of trade
unionists. He wanted the TUC to play a co-ordinating role in the campaign to
retain the check-off arrangements. A TUC working group on check-off has been
set up to assist unions.
unions are now legally obliged to reconfirm at least every three years that
their members wish to continue having union subscriptions debited from their
salaries. The unions, which will have to get this information from all their
members in the next 12 months, fear this could result in a fall in union
member-ships.
Mr Monks said he sensed a more positive feeling among the unions. He added
that the TUC wanted to work with good employers as well as expose bad
employers.
</TEXT>
