<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 93 / Licence granted for waste plant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RECHEM International, the waste management group, yesterday received a
licence to keep operating its plant at Pontypool, Gwent, under new
environmental regulations, but was told to improve monitoring of toxic
emissions.
The Pollution Inspectorate gave the plant, including a proposed new
incinerator, authorisation under the Integrated Pollution Control provisions
of the 1990 Environmental Protection Act, which are coming into force in
stages.
But following a recent Welsh Office report on levels of toxic PCB and dioxin
chemicals around the plant, Rechem has been told to make 'wide- ranging'
improvements, mainly in the next six months. These include more analysis of
emissions from the stacks, environmental monitoring near the plant, and an
assessment of on-site levels of PCBs and dioxins in the air and soil.
