<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 93 / MoD 'overruled on arms exports'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOREIGN Office officials were in favour of the government circumventing its
guidelines on exports to Iraq and Iran if it was felt to be in the 'national
interest', the Scott arms-for-Iraq inquiry heard yester-day.
Under guidelines officially in place from 1985 to late 1988, the government
was supposed not to approve exports that would 'significantly enhance the
capability of either side to prolong or exacerbate' the Gulf conflict.
But giving evidence to the inquiry, Sir David Miers, a former Foreign Office
minister, said that between 1986 and 1988 he and other officials agreed to
override military criteria when considering certain exports if it was felt
that British economic and diplomatic objectives could be better served by
their approval.
Among the factors taken into account were the views of the US and of Saudi
Arabia, as well as the potential loss of market opportunities for British
companies at a time when France was increasing its commercial presence in
the Middle East.
Documents made available to the inquiry confirm that as a result defence
equipment which some experts at the Ministry of Defence considered should
have been embargoed was exported to both Iran and Iraq. This was before
ministers at the Foreign Office, the Department of Trade and Industry, and
the MoD agreed to adopt a more flexible policy on arms in a secret policy
change at the end of 1988.
Yesterday Sir David rejected a suggestion by Lord Justice Scott that
officials had adopted a 'cynical approach' both in the way they failed to
apply the guidelines and in the bland information about government policy
that was offered to parliament.
Sir David said: 'Our approach was extremely conscientious . . . each case
was looked at very carefully and it was felt that one should be very
cautious about what should be appoved.'
Sir David is now the UK ambassador to the Netherlands. He will give further
evidence today.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>IQZ  Iraq, Middle East.
    IRZ  Iran, Middle East.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
<XX>
