<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 93 / World Trade News: Tough Gatt message on concessions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Peter Sutherland, director-general of the General Agreement on Tariffs
and Trade, is in Washington this week delivering a tough message on the need
for concessions to win a Uruguay Round deal.
Not even the US could unilaterally impose its will on others, he warned.
He placed the blame for the slow world trade negotiations squarely on the
industrialised countries, which 'have not been delivering on crucial areas'
where the poor countries can compete, while the developing world has been
taking more liberal positions.
Just as bluntly Mr Sutherland said the governments of the developing
countries must be prepared to open their textile and clothing markets to
gain access for their textiles and apparel in wealthy industrialised
countries.
On his first trip to the US since taking the helm of Gatt, Mr Sutherland is
telling administration, congressional and business leaders that December 15
is the 'immutable' deadline and that he is prepared to act 'the honest
broker' to get necessary concessions.
He stressed that the US had to get support from other nations if it wanted
to rewrite the current negotiating text.
'If there are changes sought, it's for the country to determine that there's
substantive support for them,' he said. 'Any conclusion in this Round
requires everybody to take into account that they're not the only people in
the world.'
He saw no reason for US fears about losing its sovereignty to the proposed
Multilateral Trade Organisation.
Negotiators in Geneva are trying to 'flesh out' the agreement reached by the
industrialised countries at the Tokyo economic summit. During August the
parties will be asked to obtain instructions from their governments and at
the end of the month there will be a work programme to 'map out milestones
which will give us various levels of agreements that have to be reached by
particular dates'.
</TEXT>
