to merge Kali + Salz, a BASF subsidiary, with Mitteldeutschen Kali, the east
German producer. With the merger, the Treuhand aimed to save the remaining
five eastern German mines, and reduce severe overcapacity.
As part of its merger plan, the Treuhand has already made two unprecedented
moves. First, it proposed the west German sector share the burden in
reducing the workforce. The number of jobs at Kali + Salz will be cut by
1,744 to 4,488, and at Mitteldeutschen Kali by 1,884 to 3,012.
Second, the Treuhand has taken a 49 per cent stake, worth DM1bn, in the
merger, with an option to sell its share after five years.
