<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 93 / Three nations to build warship
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRANCE, Italy and Britain have signed a memorandum of understanding to
develop and produce a new warship.
The common new generation frigate will be the first big maritime
collaboration between the three nations and aims to reduce each country's
budget by sharing costs.
It is an extension of a planned Anglo-French frigate which has been
discussed by London and Paris since 1990 and received the go-ahead the
following year. Italy joined the programme earlier this year.
The UK Defence Ministry said that although a commitment to take the project
to the production stage had been signed, the programme 'is still at a very
early stage'.
The frigate, which should be in service within seven years, is intended to
replace the Royal Navy's Type 42 air-defence destroyers, which were at the
forefront of the naval campaign in the Gulf war.
</TEXT>
