<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 93 / High Court move delays treaty: Rees-Mogg wins right to
challenge way government handled Maastricht bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT conceded yesterday that the UK's ratification of the
Maastricht treaty will have to await the outcome of a legal challenge on
behalf of the anti-Maastricht campaign.
Its decision came as the opposing camps at Westminster stepped up their
preparations for Thursday's critical Commons debate on the social chapter.
It means ratification will be delayed until the autumn.
As Tory Eurosceptics met to lay their plans, they expressed confidence that
they would defeat the government and put a further obstacle in the way of
ratification. But in an atmosphere of intrigue and bluff, the possibility of
a government deal with the nine MPs of the Ulster Unionist party was raised
as it was announced that Sir Patrick Mayhew, the Northern Ireland secretary,
would meet unionist MPs on Thursday afternoon.
With all sides agreeing that the votes of the minor parties are likely to
determine the result of the debate, there was a further glimmer of light for
the government with a split emerging among the Liberal Democrats over voting
tactics.
Although Mr John Major has said he does not regard it as a confidence issue,
a defeat would undermine his battered authority. Yesterday, even loyalists
who said they believed the government would win admitted that, on paper,
they did not see how a defeat could be avoided.
If all the opposition parties vote together and are joined by 10 Tory MPs,
the government's 18-strong overall majority would be overturned.
The Eurosceptics were encouraged by the decision of two High Court judges to
allow Lord Rees-Mogg, a leading critic of the prime minister, to apply for a
judicial review of the government's planned ratification of the treaty. At
the review, which begins next Monday, Lord Rees-Mogg will seek a court order
preventing ratification of the treaty in its present form because, he
claims, the government's approach is legally and constitutionally flawed.
The government made no attempt to block Lord Rees-Mogg's move yesterday,
saying it did not want the application obstructed. Lawyers for Mr Douglas
Hurd, the foreign secretary, went on to say the government had no intention
of ratifying the treaty before the conclusion of the court proceedings.
Downing Street emphasised that the government would oppose the substance of
the challenge.
Applying for the review, lawyers for Lord Rees-Mogg argued the government
was using the royal prerogative to bypass parliament in a way not attempted
since Stuart times. Modern legal authorities had demonstrated that the
government's attitude was legally unsustainable.
Lord Rees-Mogg's legal challenge will be based on three main grounds - the
transfer of the foreign policy prerogative to Brussels, the increase in the
powers of the European Parliament and the exclusion of the social protocol.
The judicial review is expected to be completed within the week when the
courts rise for the summer. This would leave time for any appeal by the
government to be heard during August.
At Westminster, there was confusion about how the Commons debate would be
affected by the matter's becoming sub judice as a result of the legal
challenge.
Government tactics seemed to be aimed at forming different coalitions on the
two separate votes at the end of the debate. There was a suggestion that if
the Labour amendment - that the government should not ratify the treaty
until it has committed itself to the social chapter - were passed, ministers
might not vote against the amended motion.
This was apparently intended to win support for the government on the first
vote among those Eurosceptics who want to stall ratification by ensuring
that MPs reject the final motion so that the technical requirement for a
parliamentary resolution is not met. If the Labour amendment is defeated,
the Liberal Democrats may vote with the government in order to allow
ratification to proceed.
Page 9
Lib Dems split over Maastricht strategy
Establishment thorn in Major's side
Editorial Comment, Page 13
</TEXT>
