<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 93 / International Company News: Mexican media sale nets Dollars
641m for government
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MEXICO CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Mexican government has sold two state-owned television networks, a
string of cinemas and other media companies for 2bn pesos (Dollars 641m) to
Radio-televisora del Centro, a company formed by the owners of Grupo
Elektra, the electrical and white goods chain.
The new company will be controlled by Mr Ricardo Salinas Pliego, president
and principal owner of Grupo Elektra. It will become Mexico's second-largest
media group after Televisa, the powerful television, radio and newspaper
concern.
Radiotelevisora bid some 30 per cent more than the runner-up in the
privatisation, Cosmovision.
Radiotelevisora will look for domestic and foreign partners to help it
compete with Televisa, which has about 90 per cent of Mexico's television
market and owns stakes in Univision, the principal Spanish-language station
in the US, and the Peruvian broadcaster, Radio Defusion de Peruana. Televisa
also has links with TCI, the world's largest cable company, among others.
The new company is also expected to invest heavily in improving the run-down
former state-owned cinema chain. The government recently gave the industry a
boost by removing controls on cinema ticket prices.
The government decided not to sell the state-owned newspaper El Nacional, on
the grounds that the highest offer was not sufficient.
The newspaper, which staunchly supports the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party but which is believed to be loss-making, will thus
continue to be run and subsidised by the government.
Privately-owned Grupo Elektra is Mexico's largest consumer electronics
chain, with some 275 stores. It imports, makes and assembles televisions,
white goods, radio equipment and other electronic goods, and through a
subsidiary, offers personal radio communications.
