<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 93 / Pakistan appoints caretaker premier as Sharif quits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FARHAN BOKHARI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MOEEN QURESHI, a former vice-president of the World Bank, was last night
sworn in as Pakistan's caretaker premier after the army arranged a deal
which brought Mr Nawaz Sharif's resignation as prime minister.
Mr Sharif had announced earlier in the evening that he would step down.
President Ghulam Ishaq Khan, who has been locked in a power struggle with Mr
Sharif for the last six months of the latter's 32 months in office, followed
suit shortly after appointing Mr Qureshi and dissolving the national
assembly.
Elections for the lower house of parliament have been set for October 6.
Caretaker governments are expected to be set up in Pakistan's four
provinces, where elections are scheduled for October 9. Mr Wasim Sajjad, the
Senate chairman, took over as acting president in the run-up to presidential
elections.
In an effort to ensure their impartiality, members of the interim government
would almost certainly promise not to contest the election, senior
government officials said.
As well as international experience, Mr Qureshi has the advantage of having
no overt affiliation with any political group, the officials added. His
World Bank credentials are also seen as positive for Pakistan's quest for a
Dollars 1bn (Pounds 600m) loan from the International Monetary Fund this
year.
Under the accord arranged by General Abdul Waheed, the army chief of staff,
Mr Khan is to retain his privileges for the four months until his scheduled
retirement. Ms Benazir Bhutto, the opposition leader, has agreed to the
deal, which meets her demand for fresh elections. Mr Sharif had sought to
mend fences with Ms Bhutto but was apparently unwilling to give ground.
There was virtually no progress on withdrawing the corruption charges
against Ms Bhutto, which were filed when her government was sacked in August
1990, and are unlikely ever to be proved in court.
</TEXT>
