<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 93 / Chief constables reject main elements of Sheehy report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S chief constables yesterday resoundingly rejected the central
elements of the government-appointed Sheehy committee's recommendations for
changes in police pay and conditions.
Mr John Burrow, chief constable of Essex and president of the Association of
Chief Police Officers (Acpo), said proposals in the report would damage the
morale and ethos of the police service. The association is seeking immediate
discussions with the government to express its concern.
Mr Michael Howard, home secretary, has until now drawn comfort from the fact
that the chief officers reacted with more reserve than other ranks when the
proposals were published a fortnight ago. But Acpo's formal response now
places all the service's representative organisations in opposition to the
Sheehy report.
The opposition will be expressed forcefully tomorrow evening when more than
11,000 officers are due to gather at Wembley arena in London for a
demonstration organised by the Police Federation, which represents ranks up
to chief inspector, and the Superintendents' Association. Organisers say the
meeting will demonstrate the 'outrage' felt by rank-and-file officers.
Radical proposals in the report, produced by a committee chaired by Sir
Patrick Sheehy, chairman of BAT Industries, include introducing 10-year
fixed-term contracts subsequently renewable every five years,
performance-related pay and lifting the retirement age from 55 to 60.
In its response, Acpo supports fixed-term contracts for senior officers but
not for constables, sergeants and inspectors who make up the majority of
police officers. It also opposes relating junior ranks' pay to performance.
Acpo says the proposed retirement age change, combined with recommendations
on pensions, would prevent mature entrants gaining full pensions. And, say
the chief constables, 'we doubt that the stresses and strains of operational
policing can be effectively carried out by officers approaching their 60s'.
While Acpo wants more flexibility in the management structure, it opposes a
recommendation to abolish the ranks of chief inspector, chief superintendent
and deputy chief constable.
Mr Howard will consider responses to the Sheehy report until September
before making final decisions.
Breaking into the criminal justice market, Page 10
