FT  19 JUL 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Best of the repeats: Waiting For God, outstanding comedy about two people in
a retirement home, unfairly overshadowed (because of the popularity of the
Victor Meldrew character) by 'One Foot In The Grave', Stephanie Cole and
Graham Crowden form a magnificent miniature awkward squad (8.30 BBC1); KYTV
with Angus Deayton as presenter for a naff television station; and Blott On
The Landscape (10.10 BBC1) Malcolm Bradbury's nicely judged adaptation of
Tom Sharpe's farce.
World In Action investigates the endowment mortgage business. Seventy per
cent of home owners insure their mortgages, but the programme asserts that
there is growing fear that many will fail to pay off at a high enough rate
to cover the debt (8.30 ITV).
In Panorama Tom Mangold reports on the case of the Florida dentist held
responsible for transmitting HIV to six of his patients (9.30 BBC1). Channel
4 screens a documentary, 'The Star And Its Shadow' in the Global Image slot,
looking at the darker side of the Mercedes Benz history during the period of
the Third Reich (10.55).
