<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 93 / Construction Contracts: Jamuna bridge development
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
HYUNDAI ENGINEERING AND CONSTRUCTION, based in South Korea, has put in the
lowest bid of USDollars 221m (Pounds 147m)to build the 4.8km long Jamuna
Bridge in Bangladesh.
The lowest offer for the river training works came from the Dutch company,
HAM/Van Oord ACZ JV. Under the first alternative, with freedom to procure
stones from anywhere, it bid USDollars 309m (Pounds 206m) or alternatively
USDollars 269m (Pounds 179m) providing stones were procured from
neighbouring countries like India and Bhutan.
Rendel Palmer &amp; Tritton, which has been involved in the project since 1986,
will now work with its engineering partners, NEDECO of Holland, the local
Bangladesh Consultants and the Jamuna Multipurpose Bridge Authority on
evaluating all the tenders received.
The Rendel Palmer &amp; Tritton-led design team has waited 18 months to reach
this stage following the green light from the World Bank in January 1992
after a two-year review of the economic return of the project. The tender
process was delayed by the decision of the Bangladesh government to
re-tender on the river training works.
A much higher price, USDollars 356m (Pounds 237m), was quoted in the first
bid a few months ago when the contractor envisaged procurement of stones
from countries like Malaysiaand Indonesia. The re-tendered price has been
reduced by about USDollars 100m (Pounds 67m) under the option for procuring
stones from neighbouring countries.
The bridge will be the first fixed transport link across the river, which
forms a 15km barrier, separating the western side with its fertile
north-west zone, from the eastern side containing the commercial centre
Dhaka and the primary port, Chittagong.
The crossing will comprise a bridge structure about 4.8km wide, river
training works and road embankments on the flood plain between the river
training works and the high banks.
</TEXT>
