<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 93 / Inquiry into NatWest data urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday called for a full public inquiry into National Westminster
Bank's policy of holding information about the political affiliation and
religious beliefs of some of its 6.5m personal customers.
Mr Nigel Griffiths, Labour's consumer spokesman, said that NatWest's actions
were 'a monstrous invasion of people's privacy' and called for legislation
to limit the collection and prevent the sale of sensitive personal data by
banks.
NatWest is believed to be the only one of the four big banks to record this
type of information about its customers.
The bank said yesterday that it did not solicit the information but if it
had data which it judged to be helpful in building up a profile of its
customers, it would record it in order to service them more efficiently.
NatWest added: 'Banks are about building up a relationship with their
customers. You build up the relationship by knowing about them.' It was not
able to give any examples of the circumstances in which information such as
political affiliation, religious beliefs or dietary habits might be used but
denied that it would affect the granting of loans to some customers.
Last week Mr Eric Howe, the data protection registrar, raised concerns about
the confidentiality of bank customers' personal details. He called for new
laws to stamp out the growing black market in confidential personal
information.
The black market has grown because unauthorised individuals have been able
to gain access to personal details by deceiving bank staff into supplying
data or because some staff may be knowingly providing it.
Mr John Lamidey, the assistant data protection registrar, yesterday said
that he was surprised at the type of information recorded by NatWest but
noted that it did not contravene the Data Protection Act. This obliges
organisations storing personal data on computer to register the type of data
recorded.
'Providing the purpose is lawful, the act does not lay down what information
you should hold,' he said.
Lloyds Bank yesterday said that its centralised computer system held
personal details such as religious beliefs only indirectly. For example the
file for a devout Moslem, for whom the taking of interest payments is
prohibited under Sharia law, would not state his religion but would carry
the instruction not to offer the customer details of interest-bearing
accounts.
Midland Bank said it did not store this type of information and found it
strange that NatWest did. Barclays Bank said it did not hold information
about customers' political affiliations.
