FT  19 JUL 93 / Tendering warning issued
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Tony Baldry, environment minister, issued a warning to local authorities
yesterday over compulsory competitive tendering. He said the government
would not hesitate to use its powers to force councils to re-tender if they
were found to be acting unfairly.
In a speech in Nottingham he said compulsory competitive tendering had
opened up more than Pounds 2.5bn of local services to private-sector
competition, giving local taxpayers and residents lower prices and better
services.
Mr Baldry admitted that the courts' 'wider' interpretation of the Transfer
of Undertakings (Protection of Employment) regulations, which often
guarantee the jobs and pay of the existing workforce when work is contracted
out, were 'a new factor' which private tenderers needed to consider.
But he said this should not be an obstacle. 'A Tupe-based bid will probably
have a higher up-front cost - but it involves no redundancy costs,' he said.
Mr Jack Straw, shadow environment secretary, will today call for a Commons
statement on the government's local government review. The move follows
speculation that ministers may be planning measures that will deny unitary
authority status to a number of big cities and boroughs.
