FT  19 JUL 93 / MPs attack 'Pounds 100m fees' over Maxwell collapse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEES LEVIED by accountants, lawyers and financial advisers working on the
Maxwell collapse could exceed Pounds 100m, a committee of MPs will suggest
today.
The Commons social security committee is expected to use a report on the
Maxwell pensioners to criticise the fees being charged by advisers and the
slow progress in retrieving funds on the pensioners' behalf.
Total fees charged have already exceeded Pounds 50m, the report will
indicate.
According to Mr David Shaw, Conservative MP for Dover and a committee
member, MPs expressed concern about fees and difficulties in tracing
ownership of missing pension-fund assets while hearing evidence.
Goldman Sachs, the US bank which dealt extensively for Robert Maxwell's
family and its companies, may be criticised. It emerged last week that the
bank had been asked to pay up to Pounds 56m to two pension schemes formerly
controlled by Maxwell.
The requests relate to transactions in 1990 in which Goldman acted as
purchaser for shares in Maxwell Communication Corporation from the Mirror
Group Pension Scheme and the Maxwell Communication Corporation Staff Scheme.
In May, the committee was told that two City investment banks were blocking
efforts by liquidators of the Maxwell pension fund management company to
trace the ownership of nearly Pounds 130m in missing assets.
</TEXT>
