FT  19 JUL 93 / Brooke to warn on arts spending
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Peter Brooke, the National Heritage secretary, will tell the Arts Council
this week it should be more accountable for the millions of pounds it
spends.
He will make a Commons statement following last month's report from Price
Waterhouse, the accountancy firm, which showed that the council spends 10p
on administration out of every Pounds 1 it receives for the arts.
Mr Brooke is unlikely to recommend any of the radical options proposed by
Price Waterhouse. These include streamlining the council's structure by
cutting the number of posts by 100 to about 50, saving Pounds 2.2m a year.
Price Waterhouse also suggested that disposing of the council's present
premises would save at least Pounds 1.3m.
Last year the Arts Council distributed Pounds 225m for arts projects.
