<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 93 / UN sees progress in Iraqi missile talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SENIOR UN envoy said last night he and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq
Aziz had made progress in talks to defuse a weapons crisis.
'I think we have cleared a large number of issues so now we have to conclude
and to sum up the results,' Mr Rolf Ekeus said after a meeting in Baghdad
with Mr Aziz, aimed at ending the impasse over UN demands for monitoring of
two missile-testing sites.
He said the two sides would conclude the discussions today.
The talks were unexpectedly joined by Mr Riyadh al-Qaysi, the Foreign
Ministry official who returned late last week from heading an Iraqi
delegation to the UN in New York, for talks on allowing a limited exception
to the post-Gulf war ban on the country's oil sales.
Mr Ekeus earlier said he could draw no conclusion from Mr al-Qaysi's
attendance. But the official's inclusion marks the first time Iraq has
directly linked the two UN negotiations and suggests Baghdad is seeking a
broader understanding rather than simply a solution to the missiles
stand-off.
The oil talks were suspended at Mr al-Qaysi's request. But UN diplomats
suggested the two sides had produced a draft text of an agreement.
</TEXT>
