<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 93 / McDonald's hit by Mississippi River
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A McDonald's billboard in West Quincy, Illinois, submerged at the weekend
after the Mississippi River broke through a levee protecting the only
passable bridge along a 200-mile stretch of river from St Louis to
Burlington, Iowa. Volunteers had struggled day and night for six weeks to
maintain a sandbag barrier that was keeping open the Bayview Bridge to
Quincy. But on Friday night the barrier gave way, and rushing water covered
up to 14,000 acres including the entrance to the bridge. As rain again
drenched the region yesterday, rising waters drove more people from their
homes, swamped towns and severed road and rail links. The crest of the
floods reached St Louis and meteorologists said the weather patterns causing
heavy rain could continue for several weeks. The floods, among the
Mississippi's worst on record, have inundated hundreds of thousands of
acres, driven at least 30,000 people from their homes and created what
Vice-President Al Gore compared to a sixth Great Lake.
