<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 93 / Tudjman hails bridge reopening as victory
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CROATIAN President Franjo Tudjman yesterday formally re-opened the strategic
Maslenica bridge, which joins northern Croatia with its southern Dalmatian
coast, after a delay earlier in the day when Serb forces shelled the area.
Frustrated with Serbian opposition to the opening of the bridge and in spite
of warnings from United Nations officials that it could re-ignite the
Serbo-Croat conflict, Croatia went ahead and installed the temporary pontoon
structure.
Mr Tudjman called the opening a 'great victory for Croatian politics' and a
'big step' for Croatia in re-establishing control over its territory.
Speaking in front of the ruins of the old bridge, destroyed in the 1991 war,
Mr Tudjman called on the Serbs of Knin, the centre of the self-styled Serb
state of Krajina which cuts Croatia in half, to 'get rid of their
extremists' and work with Zagreb, the Croatian capital, on the reopening of
electricity, traffic, and transport lines.
The new bridge could help bolster Mr Tudjman's sagging popularity,
especially in Dalmatia. The inhabitants of Adriatic cities are hostage to
Serb rebels within artillery range from the hinterland and are forced to
lived with daily power cuts.
</TEXT>
