<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 93 / Major steps up pressure over treaty vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR yesterday refused to countenance defeat in this week's crucial
House of Commons vote on the Maastricht treaty's social chapter as he
stepped up pressure on Conservative Euro-sceptics to fall into line.
Entering the most difficult week of his premiership, the prime minister
repeatedly expressed incredulity that any Tory MP would vote for proposals
that he said would raise unemployment and transfer 'massive' powers from the
UK to Brussels. 'I don't believe - given the nature of the social chapter -
that Conservative MPs, when they consider what it means and what it can do,
are going to do other than support the government,' Mr Major said.
Interviewed on BBC TV's On The Record, the prime minister was adamant that
Thursday's vote was not about ratifying the treaty or his own political
future. 'Here is a free-standing debate on the social chapter,' he said,
four times sidestepping the suggestion it would amount to a vote of
confidence in him.
But some Euro-sceptics immediately rejected this position and called for the
government to make it clear whether it intended to ratify Maastricht with
Britain's social chapter opt-out intact irrespective of the outcome of
Thursday's vote.
'At the present time we have to vote on hypotheticals because we do not know
if by voting for the social chapter we destroy the treaty or not,' said one
hard-core Euro-sceptic.
'This is not at all about the social chapter - it is about whether or not
the treaty proceeds,' said another Euro-sceptic.
As senior ministers said privately it was 'inconceivable' the government
would not ratify Maastricht, the prime minister dismissed as 'not remotely
likely' suggestions his current problems might trigger a leadership
challenge. He admitted recent moves to seek a judicial review of Maastricht
in the High Court might 'inhibit' ratification.
Some Euro-sceptics were yesterday confident there are enough Tory rebels to
defeat the government if none of the opposition parties break ranks.
The government is expected to wait until Wednesday before deciding whether
to increase efforts to persuade the Ulster Unionists to vote with the
government, perhaps by hinting that their longstanding demand for a Northern
Ireland select committee will be granted.
One Unionist said yesterday the party's nine MPs planned to decide how they
would vote at a meeting on Thursday morning.
Meanwhile, Mr John Smith yesterday raised expectations Labour would press
for a vote of censure if the government lost Thursday's vote and ignored the
verdict. 'If he (Mr Major) behaves outrageously and defies the will of
parliament that is a matter we must take extremely seriously,' the Labour
leader said.
His remarks came as an NOP poll for the Trades Union Congress found 44 per
cent of respondents thought the social chapter should apply to Britain as
well as other European countries, with 10 per cent neutral and 15 per cent
answering Don't Know.
Major declines to rule out extension of VAT Page 8
</TEXT>
